================================================================================
Third-party software
================================================================================

The distributed LoreGUI desktop application bundles third-party software. Their
copyright notices and license texts are reproduced in the accompanying
attribution bundles, which are GENERATED from the actual dependency graph and
verified in CI (.github/workflows/licenses.yml):

  * THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES-RUST.md
        All Rust crates statically linked into the LoreGUI binary and the
        bundled `loreserver` sidecar. This includes:
          - Epic Games' upstream `lore` crate and its sibling crates
            (lore-base, lore-credential, lore-proto, lore-transport, ...),
            MIT, Copyright (c) 2026 Epic Games, Inc.
          - The vendored `quinn-proto` fork shipped inside the `lore` repo
            (see the [patch.crates-io] in Cargo.toml).
          - ~520 further crates from crates.io, all under permissive or
            file-level weak-copyleft (MPL-2.0) terms.
        Generated with cargo-about (config: about.toml, template: about.hbs).

  * THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES-FRONTEND.md
        The production npm packages embedded in the Vite-built frontend that
        ships inside the desktop binary. Generated with
        `node frontend/scripts/gen-third-party-licenses.mjs`.

  * THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES.md
        A short index that links to both of the above.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Upstream Lore
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LoreGUI is a third-party GUI for Epic Games' Lore version control system. It
binds the upstream `lore` crate and bundles the upstream `loreserver` binary.
Lore is released by Epic Games, Inc. under the MIT License. LoreGUI is an
independent project and is not endorsed by or affiliated with Epic Games, Inc.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
License compliance
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Every dependency in the shipped binary is under a permissive license (MIT,
Apache-2.0, BSD, ISC, Zlib, BSL-1.0, Unicode, ...) or the file-level
weak-copyleft MPL-2.0. There are NO GPL / LGPL / AGPL / SSPL dependencies. The
license-generation tooling fails CI if a dependency outside the accepted set is
introduced, so this property cannot silently regress.
